ription";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:332:"A few months ago I did a re-write of the DOM access functionality used by Windmill and various other projects of mine and the result was a wrapper around ElementsLib called lookupNode. I use this all over internally but until today didn&#8217;t realize that it could be hugely helpful for test developers and people trying [&#8230;]";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"xmlns";a:6:{s:7:"content";s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";s:3:"wfw";s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";s:2:"dc";s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";s:4:"atom";s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";s:2:"sy";s:44:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/syndication/";s:5:"slash";s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";}}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:0:"";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"xmlns";a:6:{s:7:"content";s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";s:3:"wfw";s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";s:2:"dc";s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";s:4:"atom";s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";s:2:"sy";s:44:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/syndication/";s:5:"slash";s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";}}}}s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";a:1:{s:7:"encoded";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:1780:"<p>A few months ago I did a re-write of the DOM access functionality used by Windmill and various other projects of mine and the result was a wrapper around ElementsLib called lookupNode. I use this all over internally but until today didn&#8217;t realize that it could be hugely helpful for test developers and people trying to debug their applications.</p>\n<p>The following list are the different options you have for looking up your node:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>link</li>\n<li>xpath</li>\n<li>id</li>\n<li>name</li>\n<li>value</li>\n<li>classname</li>\n<li>tagname</li>\n<li>label</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Keep in mind that we iterate all iframes we can access in the window if the node isn&#8217;t found in the page document. lookupNode takes an object, like so:</p>\n<p><code><br />\nvar myNode = lookupNode({id:''myNodeId''});<br />\n</code></p>\n<p>The very interesting use case we had today was the need to access and parse data from a link on a page in a Python test, I believe the final result looked something like the following:<br />\n<code><br />\nurl = client.commands.execJS(code="lookupNode({link:''Link Text''}).href")["result"]<br />\n#url parsing in python goes here into needed_value<br />\nclient.asserts.assertValue({id:''mycheckbox'', validator=needed_value})<br />\n</code><br />\n<br />\n<div id="attachment_114" class="wp-caption alignnone" style="width: 491px"><img class="size-full wp-image-114" title="lookupNode in Action" src="http://www.adamchristian.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/01/picture-11.png" alt="lookupNode in Action" width="481" height="314" /><p class="wp-caption-text">lookupNode in Action</p></div><br />\n<br />\nI hope someone finds this useful, the abstracted standalone ElementsLib for the content space <a href="http://code.google.com/p/elementslib/">can be found here!</a></p>\n";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"xmlns";a:6:{s:7:"content";s:40:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/";s:3:"wfw";s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";s:2:"dc";s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";s:4:"atom";s:27:"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom";s:2:"sy";s:44:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/syndication/";s:5:"slash";s:38:"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/";}}}}s:36:"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/";a:1:{s:10:"commentRss";a:1:{i:0;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:46:"http://www.adamchristian.com/archives/111/feed";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"xmlns";a:6:{s:7:"content";s:40:"http://purl.